2026-04-16 07:50:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module indicator LED circuit open positions (1-8)'] hypothesis_explanation="Upon review of the symptoms and inspection information, the physical removal of all indicator LEDs and their resistors from the control modules (positions 1-8) has left open circuits in parallel at each module. However, crucially, the main power path through each control module is still through the switches themselves (which remain closed/on, according to the scenario). Open LEDs and their resistors alone, being paralleled rather than in series, would not open the power path for the lamp, so the lamp should function when all switches are on. Therefore, the persistent fault is not due to missing indicator components, nor is it in the load module or its diode. All visual connections and polarities were inspected and found correct. The only remaining plausible root cause—since all other modules check out and the lamp circuit cannot be tested—is a fault in the power supply module's output wiring: a break, failed solder joint, or in-module cable failure behind the visual indicator (which works due to being wired before the output connection). This could allow the supply LED to still operate while output to the modules is interrupted. Thus, I suspect a hidden output fault in the power supply module's output line."
