2026-04-16 07:50:41 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module wiring or PCB traces (LED branch open in control modules 1-8)'] hypothesis_explanation="The circuit was designed with removable indicator LEDs and resistors on parallel branches to the main switchable path in each control module. With the LEDs and series resistors physically absent, the parallel branches are now open. However, this should NOT interrupt current through the main series switch contacts (the load current path). Since neither the load nor the module LEDs work, and replacing module LEDs and resistors did not help, it is likely that the main power path through each control module was improperly designed such that removal of the parallel LED/resistor also opens the switch's main path—this could be due to a PCB layout issue or wiring error such that the switch cannot close the circuit unless the LED circuit is complete. Thus, the open circuit at the LED branch also leaves the switch output open, breaking the series path and preventing the load from turning on."
